## What Is Rhetoric?

Rhetoric is the art of using language effectively — to teach, to delight, and to persuade. It is not the art of manipulation or deception (that is *sophistry*, rhetoric's corruption); it is the art of presenting truth in ways that move audiences to embrace it and act on it.

In the ancient Greek world, rhetoric was inseparable from civic life. Democratic Athens required citizens to speak in the assembly and courts; the ability to argue one's case persuasively was not a luxury but a necessity. This is why [Plato](article.html?id=plato)'s criticisms of the Sophists — professional teachers of rhetoric who claimed to make the weaker argument appear the stronger — were so pointed: they were corrupting a civic essential by severing it from truth.

## Aristotle's Theory of Rhetoric

[Aristotle](article.html?id=aristotle)'s *Rhetoric* (c. 335 BC) is the foundational text of the subject and remains the most systematic analysis of persuasion in Western thought. Aristotle identified three modes of persuasion:

| Mode | Greek Term | Definition |
|---|---|---|
| Appeal to character | *Ethos* | The speaker's credibility and trustworthiness |
| Appeal to emotion | *Pathos* | Moving the audience's feelings |
| Appeal to reason | *Logos* | Logical argument and evidence |

Aristotle argued that all three are legitimate — good rhetoric uses all three in appropriate proportion. A speaker with no credibility (*ethos*) will not be believed; a speech with no emotional resonance (*pathos*) will not move; a speech with no logical substance (*logos*) will not persuade the intellect. The great orators — [Cicero](article.html?id=cicero), Daniel Webster, [Abraham Lincoln](article.html?id=civil-war) — combined all three masterfully.

:::dropdown The Five Canons of Rhetoric
Ancient rhetoricians (especially Cicero and Quintilian) organized the practice of rhetoric into five canons — the stages of preparing and delivering a speech:

1. **Inventio (Invention)**: Finding the arguments — discovering what can be said on behalf of your case. Includes determining your central proposition, finding proofs, and anticipating objections.
2. **Dispositio (Arrangement)**: Organizing the speech for maximum effect. Classical arrangement: exordium (introduction), narratio (background), confirmatio (proof), refutatio (refutation of objections), peroratio (conclusion).
3. **Elocutio (Style)**: Choosing the right words — clarity, appropriateness, elegance. Includes figures of speech (metaphor, anaphora, chiasmus) and levels of style (plain, middle, grand).
4. **Memoria (Memory)**: Memorizing the speech so it can be delivered naturally without reading from notes.
5. **Pronuntiatio (Delivery)**: Voice, gesture, facial expression, posture — the physical presentation of the speech.

These five canons remain an excellent practical guide to preparing any formal presentation, sermon, or argument.
:::

## Cicero and Roman Oratory

[Cicero](article.html?id=cicero) (106–43 BC) was the greatest orator of the ancient world and his Latin prose remains the gold standard of the Western rhetorical tradition. His *De Oratore* (*On the Orator*) set out a vision of the ideal orator: not merely a technician of persuasion but a man of broad learning who combines philosophical depth, legal knowledge, historical awareness, and moral seriousness with technical skill.

Cicero's ideal orator is a civic statesman who uses the power of language in service of the republic and justice. This vision — that eloquence should serve truth and the common good — became the foundation of Christian homiletics.

## Augustine and Christian Rhetoric

[Augustine of Hippo](article.html?id=augustine) was trained as a professional rhetorician before his conversion to Christianity. In *On Christian Doctrine* (Book IV), he made the decisive case that Christians should use rhetoric — the full classical tradition — in service of the Gospel:

> "Since rhetoric is used to give persuasion to both truth and falsehood, who would dare to say that truth should stand in the person of its defenders unarmed against falsehood?"

Augustine argued that the preacher should aim to teach (doctrine), to delight (hold attention), and to move (compel action) — Cicero's three purposes of oratory — all in service of the divine Word. This sanctified the classical rhetorical tradition for Christian use and shaped the practice of preaching from Augustine to the present day.

## Rhetoric and the Liberal Arts

In the medieval university, rhetoric was one of the three arts of the *trivium* — the foundational curriculum of [grammar](article.html?id=latin), [logic](article.html?id=formal-logic), and rhetoric that every student mastered before proceeding to the four mathematical arts of the *quadrivium*. Together they formed the classical liberal arts curriculum that produced the greatest minds of Western civilization.

The *trivium* remains the best model for foundational education:
- **Grammar**: Understanding language precisely — reading and writing well
- **Logic**: Thinking clearly — distinguishing valid from invalid reasoning
- **Rhetoric**: Speaking and writing persuasively — moving audiences to truth

A student who has mastered the trivium can learn anything. Students who lack it are easily manipulated by whoever controls the medium.

## Rhetoric in Preaching and Public Life

The greatest speeches in American history are masterworks of classical rhetoric:

- **Lincoln's Second Inaugural Address**: A model of ethos (moral authority earned through suffering), logos (reasoned argument about the war's meaning), and pathos (the tragic weight of "malice toward none, charity for all").
- **[Martin Luther King Jr.'s "I Have a Dream"](article.html?id=civil-war)**: An extended anaphora ("I have a dream that one day...") combining biblical prophecy with the Declaration of Independence's natural rights argument.
- **Patrick Henry's "Give Me Liberty or Give Me Death"**: Pure deliberative rhetoric demanding a decision.

These speeches worked because their authors were steeped in the Bible, the classical tradition, and the lived moral authority to speak. Rhetoric without moral substance is noise; rhetoric with moral substance can change the world.

